    {
      "id": "44ca04b467445d0ebfd0da36067c8a3d36784d7a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2016-06-02 21:32:03.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1\n\n(4 comments)\n\nAndriy, sometimes patches slip through the cracks, especially in cases like this when the patch was submitted during Christmas holidays.  That is especially true if there are no reviewers assigned.\n\nIf your patches are not getting the needed attention, please assign reviewers (that could be me and I may reassign it to someone else at Intel), or anyone else that is familiar with this code, including developers from Seagate.  If it is still not getting attention, you can add additional comments in the patch requesting reviewers' attention as many other developers do (e.g. \"please review\", \"ping reviewers\", etc.).\n\nIf that still isn't working, the issue can be raised on the bi-weekly Lustre Working Group call, or in the weekly Seagate meetings.  I don't think anyone likes duplicating the effort to debug and fix bugs in the code.\n\nIt would be useful to land the test case if you could refresh this patch on top of master.  To avoid running all of the tests that are unrelated to the added test case, the patch could use the new \"trivial\" keyword like:\n\n Test-Parameters: trivial testlist=recovery-small\n\nOtherwise this patch could be abandoned.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
